Q2 ---  SPARK VS MAPREDUCE
  
┌──────────────────┬──────────────────┬──────────────────┐
│ Parameter        │ Disk-Based       │ In-Memory        │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ Storage          │ Disk (EBS/HDFS)  │ RAM              │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ Speed            │ Slow             │ 10-100x Faster   │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ I/O Cost         │ High             │ Low              │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────┼──────────────────┤

  Spark processes data in-memory (100× faster for iterative/real-time workloads), 
  while MapReduce writes intermediate results to disk (slower, disk-based batch processing).
    
"Disk-Based (100GB): 
 "Step1(Map) → Write 50GB to EBS (5min)"
 "Step2(Shuffle) → Write 25GB to EBS (3min)"
 "Step3(Reduce) → Write Final (2min) = 10min total, 3 disk writes = SLOW"

"In-Memory (100GB):  
  Step1→Keep 50GB in RAM(2min) → Step2→Process in RAM(0.5min) → Step3→Write Final(0.5min) = 3min"


